07219nam a22011655i 9781487532642DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875326427 a10.3138/97814875326422doi  a(DE-B1597)551075  a(OCoLC)1128819513  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPA6825b.W35 2020 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a873/.0122300aWalking through Elysium :bVergil’s Underworld and the Poetics of Tradition /ced. by Micah Young Myers, Bill Gladhill. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPhoenix Supplementary Volumes00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- t1. Into the Woods (Via Cuma 320, Bacoli) -- t2. A Walk in Vergil’s Footsteps: Statius on the Via Domitiana -- t3. In the Sibyl’s Cave: Vergilian Prophecy and Mary Shelley’s Last Man -- t4. Exploring the Forests of Antiquity: The Golden Bough and Early Modern Spirituality -- t5. Aeneas’ Steps -- t6. Vergil’s Underworld and the Afterlife of Lovers and Love Poets -- t7. Vergilian Underworlds in Ovid -- t8. Mortem aliquid ultra est: Vergil’s Underworld in Senecan Tragedy -- t9. Servius on Sinners and Punishments in Vergil’s Underworld -- t10. Paradise and Performance in Vergil’s Underworld and Horace’s Carmen Saeculare -- t11. Why Isn’t Homer in Vergil’s Underworld? – and Other Notable Absences -- t12. The Silence of Aeneid 6 in Augustine’s Confessions -- t13. Spiritualism as Textual Practice -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tPHOENIX SUPPLEMENTARY VOLUMES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWalking through Elysium stresses the subtle and intricate ways writers across time and space wove Vergil’s underworld in Aeneid 6 into their works. These allusions operate on many levels, from the literary and political to the religious and spiritual. Aeneid 6 reshaped prior philosophical, religious, and poetic traditions of underworld descents, while offering a universalizing account of the spiritual that could accommodate prior as well as emerging religious and philosophical systems. Vergil’s underworld became an archetype, a model flexible enough to be employed across genres, and periods, and among differing cultural and religious contexts. The essays in this volume speak to Vergil’s incorporation of and influence on literary representations of underworlds, souls, afterlives, prophecies, journeys, and spaces, from sacred and profane to wild and civilized, tracing the impact of Vergil’s underworld on authors such as Ovid, Seneca, Statius, Augustine, and Shelley, from Pagan and Christian traditions through Romantic and Spiritualist readings. Walking through Elysium asserts the deep and lasting influence of Vergil’s underworld from the moment of its publication to the present day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aVoyages to the otherworld in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAeneid.  aAugustine.  aChristian.  aOvid.  aPagan.  aRomantic.  aRome.  aSeneca.  aShelley.  aStatius.  aVergil.  aVirgil.  aclassical literature.  adeath.  aliterary reception.  apoetry.  aspirituality.  atradition.  aunderworld.1 aBarchiesi, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladhill, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladhill, Bill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGowers, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrero De Jáuregui, Miguel, econtributor.